Hi I was trying out the new `split()` functionality to split a test set into test and validation set. When the `BucketIterator` is being set up from a newly split dataset the sorting fails because `dataset.sort_key` is None. Looking at the `split()`  function I see that a new instance of type `Dataset` is created in which `sort_key` is None by default:
```
def split():
...
if not stratified:
            train_data, test_data, val_data = rationed_split(self.examples, train_ratio,
                                                             test_ratio, val_ratio, rnd)
            return tuple(Dataset(d, self.fields)
                         for d in (train_data, val_data, test_data) if d)
```

I guess one way would be to explicitly copy the `sort_key` into the new instance. A more generic way could be to make a copy of the current instance and replace only the `examples` attribute but I'm not sure if that is really needed.

Thanks!

Result from User testing summary:

We found that user have trouble understanding the button icons and 3 file stage sections. So, the fail rates here are high and some user couldn't even go through the process to get to the later steps;
Some have been mentioned here: https://github.com/jupyterlab/jupyterlab-git/issues/162

1. Select a file to track  
Correct Action: click [ ] icon in right of that filename 
1st time fail rate: 76.00% , 2nd time fail rate: 44.00%
Mistakes: 
--Right click on file item for "Track" option (8), 
--Double clicked on the file name (5),  
--Single clicked on the file name (2),
--user tried to drag and drop file into staged (2), 
--user clicked on stage all instead of the individual file (1) 
--Clicked on collapse icon in Unstaged section header (1)

2. Track all files 
Correct Action: click [ ] icon at top of Untracked section
1st time fail rate: 73.08%, 2nd time fail rate: 19.23%
--Did not understand and did not track any of the untracked file (10), 
--Clicked on each individual item (3), 
--Tried to highlight all files and drag and drop under unstaged section(3)  
--Clicked on discard icon (1) 
--Clicked on an unstaged file in file browser (1) 
--Clicked on branch icon (1)

**Cause:**  
Icons are confusing, user cannot directly link icon with the action (especially ‘track’);
‘Act’ and ‘Act All’ icon are the same, hard for user to understand the difference;
Three sections are not well separated;
Common user habits (try to drag file around, right click to find options, 
highlight multiple files to perform ‘Act All’);
Unfamiliar with Git based version control;

**Solution:**
Re-design action icons;
Distinguish ‘Act’ and ‘Act all’ button;
Clearly separate each section from each other (use background or outline color);
Follow common user habits:
		--add function into right click button ;
		--allow drag file across fields (challenging);
